				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\text {GeV}$$\end{document}. Computations and measurements of the rejection, especially absolute rejections, are typically associated with large uncertainties due to ambiguities in the definition of the denominator, and the diversity of the sources of background. The factors mentioned above are similar to those published in Table 3 of the ATLAS Run-1 publication [3] when these considerations are taken into account.

A considerable challenge at the LHC experiments is to differentiate the prompt production of electrons, muons, and photons in signal processes (from the hard-scattering vertex, or from the decay of heavy resonances such as Higgs, W\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
